</p>
<p>Delivering your message requires tact and sensitivity.  Avoid clichés or overly formal language.  Instead, focus on personal memories or qualities of the deceased that you admired.  Timing is also essential; offering condolences promptly shows you care, but avoid overwhelming the family immediately after the funeral. Allow space for them to grieve and then reach out with a thoughtful gesture or message.  A simple phone call, a heartfelt card, or a carefully worded email can all be effective ways to convey your support.</p>
    

